WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:00.880
Good afternoon, everyone,

2
00:00:02.480 --> 00:00:05.760
and welcome to our session on intratumor drug responses.

3
00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:09.600
My name is Oliver Jonas, and I'm the chair of this session.

4
00:00:10.490 --> 00:00:13.110
The focus of our session today

5
00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:18.000
addresses one of the central challenges in precision oncology, and that's really a

6
00:00:18.020 --> 00:00:20.260
twofold question. The first part is: how do we understand

7
00:00:22.380 --> 00:00:25.700
what the drug is actually doing inside of a patient's

8
00:00:25.720 --> 00:00:27.680
tumor when the treatment is happening?

9
00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:32.580
And then a question related to that is: how do we connect that information to what

10
00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:34.440
we routinely measure in the clinic

11
00:00:35.460 --> 00:00:37.900
through the imaging and pathology and the clinical outcomes,

12
00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:40.880
such as symptom progression and survival?

13
00:00:43.480 --> 00:00:44.620
In many clinical settings,

14
00:00:45.820 --> 00:00:46.580
what we still see

15
00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:49.860
is basically what's outlined here.

16
00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:52.160
Let's see if I can show my mouse.

17
00:00:55.600 --> 00:00:55.680
No.

18
00:00:56.980 --> 00:00:58.960
I guess we don't have a cursor yet. But

19
00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:01.420
is that there's essentially

20
00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:07.460
some baseline biopsy in some tumors, molecular profiling that's done,

21
00:01:08.020 --> 00:01:08.760
and then the patient

22
00:01:10.580 --> 00:01:14.120
embarks on a course of treatment, and then we typically monitor that treatment with

23
00:01:14.180 --> 00:01:14.540
imaging

24
00:01:15.620 --> 00:01:17.880
over the course of weeks to months.

25
00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:20.090
And oftentimes, the first measurement

26
00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:24.560
could be an MRI or a CT, is often about six to eight weeks out.

27
00:01:26.220 --> 00:01:29.950
And then over the course of several months, we assess clinical responses and

28
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:30.420
outcomes.

29
00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:35.090
But what we really miss is what's actually happening inside the tumor,

30
00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:37.640
and that's the focus of this session.

31
00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:45.179
Oops, let's see. The slides are not advancing.

32
00:01:45.240 --> 00:01:45.900
Is there any way to

33
00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:47.640
activate that?

34
00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:49.700
Thank you so much. Okay.

35
00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:54.240
So what we'd like to learn more about is that critical window

36
00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:58.520
from when we start treatment to when we do that first imaging and when we

37
00:01:58.620 --> 00:02:02.520
understand what happens at the larger scale, what happens at the size of tumor

38
00:02:02.540 --> 00:02:02.980
shrinkage

39
00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:04.760
or tumor progression,

40
00:02:05.800 --> 00:02:08.420
and certainly what happens in terms of patient outcome and survival.

41
00:02:10.741 --> 00:02:14.100
During those initial days and weeks, we miss

42
00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:19.100
all the molecular biology and all the critical cell biology in terms of target

43
00:02:19.140 --> 00:02:22.560
engagement, in terms of pathway signaling shifts, all the metabolic

44
00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:24.420
reprogramming that happens pretty rapidly,

45
00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:28.859
and the early events of immune modulation.

46
00:02:31.820 --> 00:02:35.800
And so as a result of that, the clinical decisions are lagging far behind

47
00:02:35.840 --> 00:02:36.700
the tumor biology.

48
00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:47.600
So the opportunity here is to use new technologies, such

49
00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:51.320
as the implantable microdevices that we'll introduce today, and

50
00:02:51.420 --> 00:02:52.340
spatial profiling

51
00:02:53.260 --> 00:02:56.760
of drug responses in the tumors that look at protein and signaling,

52
00:02:57.220 --> 00:02:59.090
the networks that look at metabolic mapping,

53
00:03:01.380 --> 00:03:02.700
and that can do all that

54
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.210
in a spatially intact way that let us not only understand the bulk measurements,

55
00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:09.500
but also the single-cell

56
00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:14.580
responses and cell-to-cell interactions that make up

57
00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:18.020
the overall response of the tumor.

58
00:03:18.820 --> 00:03:21.960
So with that, I'd like to introduce our first speaker,

59
00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:26.380
Professor Sean Davidson from Northwestern University.

60
00:03:26.420 --> 00:03:30.290
He has done incredible work in tumor biology with a particular

61
00:03:30.340 --> 00:03:31.660
focus on tumor metabolism.

62
00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:36.190
His work has pioneered the use of spatial mass spectrometry techniques to map the

63
00:03:36.220 --> 00:03:38.180
distribution of metabolites within tumors

64
00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:43.000
and provided new insight into how metabolic networks are

65
00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:46.700
rewired in response to therapy. He has applied these approaches

66
00:03:46.750 --> 00:03:48.060
across multiple cancer types,

67
00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:53.660
including prostate, pancreatic, and breast cancers, and we're very excited to hear

68
00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:56.220
about his work. So please join me in welcoming Dr. Davidson.

69
00:04:10.340 --> 00:04:12.880
Great. Thank you for the kind introduction.

70
00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:17.079
It's very exciting to be here today to share this work, which

71
00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:20.140
has been ongoing since I was a graduate student.

72
00:04:20.399 --> 00:04:20.680
And

73
00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:25.140
before I jump into the main story, looking at cell type-specific metabolism,

74
00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:27.320
I'll go into a little bit of background about

75
00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:29.860
how we got here.

76
00:04:32.060 --> 00:04:32.300
So,

77
00:04:36.540 --> 00:04:38.980
it starts with the invention of the implantable microdevice.

78
00:04:39.020 --> 00:04:42.800
So I was a PhD student at the Koch Institute at MIT, and I was

79
00:04:42.840 --> 00:04:46.760
working one floor below Oli when he invented this

80
00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:48.340
device in Bob Langer's lab.

81
00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:52.040
And this was really the point of the Koch Institute, I think.

82
00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:56.040
Phil Sharp wanted convergence and the

83
00:04:56.680 --> 00:05:00.210
convergence between scientists and engineers, and it was just such an exciting

84
00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:01.200
place to be.

85
00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:05.080
At first, we would sit in the lunchrooms, and people would talk about, as a

86
00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:08.520
biologist, I'm hearing about quantum dots and all kinds of things.

87
00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:11.580
But it really worked, and I think this is living proof.

88
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:13.260
So I'm happy to share this.

89
00:05:14.980 --> 00:05:18.920
So Oli invented this implantable microdevice, which is about the size of a grain of

90
00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:20.160
rice, and you can

91
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:21.200
put

92
00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:24.740
many different drugs into that device, and then you can

93
00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:28.900
implant it into a tumor, and then you resect the tumor,

94
00:05:29.560 --> 00:05:33.500
and then you section through the device and you can get

95
00:05:34.580 --> 00:05:36.870
spatial readouts, and you can get drug response

96
00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:42.350
within the tumor itself. So you implant it into the mouse,

97
00:05:42.440 --> 00:05:46.040
and now there are many clinical trials, I think

98
00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:46.640
13

99
00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:50.340
human clinical trials using this device.

100
00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:51.480
And

101
00:05:52.460 --> 00:05:56.130
you implant it, and then after a certain amount of time, and this is very different

102
00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:59.620
for every assay, if we are looking at protein or if we are looking at metabolites

103
00:06:00.580 --> 00:06:04.300
we might change the duration, but it can go from hours to days to

104
00:06:04.360 --> 00:06:07.630
weeksAnd then we can extract it and do

105
00:06:07.630 --> 00:06:09.400
different assays on this.

106
00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:10.460
So

107
00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:12.150
at the time, I was

108
00:06:14.020 --> 00:06:17.970
in Matt Vander Heiden's lab studying cancer cell metabolism,

109
00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:21.520
and we were working with and collaborating with Dafna Bar-Sagi at

110
00:06:21.560 --> 00:06:25.400
NYU. And Dafna made the original observation about a process called

111
00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:29.380
macropinocytosis, and that was that when you inject oncogenic RAS into rat

112
00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:33.180
embryonic fibroblasts, they transform, and they have this thing where they start

113
00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:35.580
doing membrane ruffling that's actin-mediated.

114
00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:38.940
Now, this is bulk endocytosis.

115
00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:43.640
It wasn't appreciated as its own cell biology process until

116
00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:47.380
the '90s, but this was really important.

117
00:06:47.580 --> 00:06:47.740
Now,

118
00:06:48.980 --> 00:06:51.420
it's interesting to think about this because,

119
00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:55.740
in many ways, macropinocytosis doesn't make a lot of sense.

120
00:06:56.320 --> 00:07:00.020
Cells work really hard. They spend a lot of energy trying to maintain chemical

121
00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:03.840
gradients across their membranes and trying to get nutrients

122
00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:07.560
inside. And so by doing this random, non-specific

123
00:07:07.570 --> 00:07:11.480
process of macropinocytosis, all of those things kind of go away.

124
00:07:11.520 --> 00:07:15.440
So it was unknown at the time, even though we knew that the cancer cells were

125
00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:18.760
doing this, it was unknown why they were doing that.

126
00:07:19.300 --> 00:07:22.820
So it was only years later when Cosimo Commisso

127
00:07:23.340 --> 00:07:27.200
joined Dafna's lab and was doing experiments, and that's where

128
00:07:27.720 --> 00:07:31.360
I jumped into this project. So Cosimo did a really interesting experiment

129
00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:32.540
where he

130
00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:37.600
took RAS transform cells, which are critically dependent on glutamine in

131
00:07:37.620 --> 00:07:37.940
vitro.

132
00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:42.550
Many of you have grown lots of cancer cells, and you know you have to add

133
00:07:42.560 --> 00:07:45.560
glutamine, and you know if you don't have glutamine, it doesn't go so well.

134
00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:50.660
And he made an observation that he could grow these cancer

135
00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:53.970
cells successfully in low-glutamine conditions

136
00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:57.200
if he supplemented extracellular protein.

137
00:07:57.590 --> 00:08:01.570
And so the logic followed that maybe these cells are taking up protein into

138
00:08:01.620 --> 00:08:05.380
the cell, breaking it down into the constituent amino acids, and then that's what's

139
00:08:05.420 --> 00:08:07.980
feeding the cancer cells. And indeed, that's what happened.

140
00:08:08.020 --> 00:08:11.160
And so this is what was going on. We grew

141
00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:15.520
13C yeast-labeled protein, and we fed it to cancer cells, and

142
00:08:15.560 --> 00:08:19.320
we realized that about 30%, and it depends on the system, but somewhere

143
00:08:19.360 --> 00:08:22.900
around 30 or 50% of free amino acids in K-RAS transform

144
00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:25.000
cells come from extracellular protein.

145
00:08:25.540 --> 00:08:27.800
So this was really exciting, and this was all happening in a dish.

146
00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:32.920
And we wanted to know how much of this is happening in vivo, what are the relevant

147
00:08:32.980 --> 00:08:36.870
substrates, and Ali walked through the lab with a prototype of this

148
00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:40.260
microdevice, and I was looking for people to

149
00:08:41.040 --> 00:08:42.400
have a metabolic application.

150
00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:49.820
So we did this first experiment with the microdevice where we implant it

151
00:08:49.880 --> 00:08:53.840
into two xenograft cell lines, and we

152
00:08:53.910 --> 00:08:57.020
deliver rhodamine-labeled dextran or DQ-BSA.

153
00:08:57.460 --> 00:09:01.400
DQ-BSA is a caged fluorophore of bovine serum albumin,

154
00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:05.660
and you can see in the cells that have K-RAS transformation that the

155
00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:09.380
cells take in albumin or they take in the heavy labeled protein,

156
00:09:09.900 --> 00:09:13.860
and they also take in the DQ-BSA. And it's

157
00:09:13.880 --> 00:09:16.640
important, this caged fluorophore, this means that it goes to the lysosome,

158
00:09:17.740 --> 00:09:21.710
and that's how it's uncaged. So not only is it going in, but it's also going

159
00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:26.200
into the lysosome, and that makes sense with the free amino acid

160
00:09:26.540 --> 00:09:30.340
observation we saw. And in contrast, BxPC-3, not a

161
00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:34.040
K-RAS transform cancer cell line, does not do that.

162
00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:40.120
So we wanted to go a little bit further with that, and that's where MALDI imaging

163
00:09:40.160 --> 00:09:43.440
mass spectrometry, which is the main focus of my lab, comes into play.

164
00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:43.780
So

165
00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:47.660
MALDI is a

166
00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:52.120
way to do spatial metabolomics. I'm not going to go into it too much today,

167
00:09:52.540 --> 00:09:54.640
even though that's normally what I would exclusively talk about.

168
00:09:55.740 --> 00:09:59.540
But you can take a frozen tissue section and coat it with a matrix,

169
00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:03.590
and then you ionize it with this laser,

170
00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:07.600
and you can get a small molecule spatial

171
00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:08.880
resolution of

172
00:10:09.740 --> 00:10:13.460
around 15 to 20 micron. And there's a lot in the

173
00:10:13.500 --> 00:10:15.940
works and in development to improve that.

174
00:10:16.560 --> 00:10:20.520
And this was a very useful technique to study this process because then we

175
00:10:20.560 --> 00:10:24.079
could actually use the microdevice, put it into a K-RAS transform tumor,

176
00:10:24.519 --> 00:10:28.440
and we could deliver an inhibitor of macropinocytosis

177
00:10:28.480 --> 00:10:32.340
called EIPA. And so the logic was that if you deliver

178
00:10:32.400 --> 00:10:36.280
EIPA and inhibit macropinocytosis, you're cutting off the nutrient supply

179
00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:40.080
line, and therefore you may expect depleted amino acid

180
00:10:40.120 --> 00:10:43.620
levels in the tumor. And so we delivered that, and so we used MALDI to

181
00:10:43.700 --> 00:10:47.580
visualize not only the distribution of EIPA, and that's important, and I think in

182
00:10:47.600 --> 00:10:50.720
this educational session, I'm going to emphasize the different ways that we can use

183
00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:51.120
MALDI.

184
00:10:52.620 --> 00:10:56.120
So you can use EIPA, and then we saw in that

185
00:10:56.540 --> 00:10:57.120
cell line, so

186
00:10:58.080 --> 00:10:59.640
this is the K-RAS transform line,

187
00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:05.400
that EIPA has an effect and there's a decrease

188
00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:09.180
in amino acids, and it's better seen below here.

189
00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:14.000
So this was the beginning of everything and putting everything together.

190
00:11:14.050 --> 00:11:16.860
And then we started to ask what else could we do with the microdevice?

191
00:11:16.920 --> 00:11:20.520
What else can we deliver? And so I spent a little extra time in

192
00:11:20.540 --> 00:11:23.500
Boston before I went to develop this mass spec

193
00:11:24.120 --> 00:11:26.640
technology in my next step. And

194
00:11:28.060 --> 00:11:31.740
again, in the spirit of an educational section, we've delivered a lot of

195
00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:35.540
diverse molecules. I think we would probably have a pipeline number on the

196
00:11:35.560 --> 00:11:37.440
percentage that we've actually done.

197
00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:41.140
I think some of these, we had a nice base editor, so we can deliver base

198
00:11:41.220 --> 00:11:42.140
editors.

199
00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:44.780
We can do genome editing.

200
00:11:46.580 --> 00:11:50.539
I particularly like this antisense oligo approach because you can

201
00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:53.560
kind of buy them off the shelf and put them into the microdevice and then deliver

202
00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:56.460
them. So it's great to assess essential genes and

203
00:11:58.420 --> 00:12:00.960
test hypotheses around that. And we can deliver

204
00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:05.048
CRI.We've delivered inhibitors and enzymes,

205
00:12:05.108 --> 00:12:08.988
and what's really cool about this is you can actually deliver

206
00:12:09.388 --> 00:12:13.308
the drug, and then you can actually use MALDI to see how the

207
00:12:13.318 --> 00:12:15.768
drug is metabolized. So we have a CDK4/6 inhibitor.

208
00:12:16.208 --> 00:12:19.948
We can see the parent molecule, and then we can also see the metabolite

209
00:12:19.968 --> 00:12:22.448
products that you might expect from that process.

210
00:12:22.868 --> 00:12:26.608
So it's a very powerful thing, and you could imagine implanting this into a liver

211
00:12:26.648 --> 00:12:28.528
or into a tumor. And I like to think about it

212
00:12:29.368 --> 00:12:33.008
as a way that it's kind of a way to reverse efficacy.

213
00:12:33.268 --> 00:12:36.708
So you don't always know if the drug is going to get there when you dose it

214
00:12:36.768 --> 00:12:40.428
systemically, but you know at least you know if it does get there,

215
00:12:40.668 --> 00:12:44.068
that it will or will not work. And I think this approach uses that.

216
00:12:44.098 --> 00:12:47.368
And then it's a different engineering problem to actually get the

217
00:12:47.408 --> 00:12:50.268
therapeutic to the tumor.

218
00:12:51.228 --> 00:12:53.788
We're doing some other things in that space.

219
00:12:54.408 --> 00:12:58.128
But one thing we thought was it might be interesting to use this to try to

220
00:12:58.168 --> 00:13:01.578
study immune cells in the native microenvironment.

221
00:13:02.108 --> 00:13:05.718
So we know that tumor metabolism shapes the immune response, and

222
00:13:05.988 --> 00:13:09.438
lactate suppresses T cells, adenosine shuts down

223
00:13:09.528 --> 00:13:13.188
antigen production presentation, and

224
00:13:13.228 --> 00:13:15.118
nutrient competition can starve immune cells.

225
00:13:15.148 --> 00:13:18.658
There's probably a million other things that we still have yet to discover,

226
00:13:19.208 --> 00:13:20.288
inhibitory molecules.

227
00:13:21.208 --> 00:13:25.188
And so it's really exciting, but it's a very difficult thing, and so measuring

228
00:13:25.208 --> 00:13:28.088
this in the tissue has been impossible until

229
00:13:29.188 --> 00:13:29.608
recently.

230
00:13:30.408 --> 00:13:30.688
And

231
00:13:31.568 --> 00:13:32.788
so most approaches were using

232
00:13:33.628 --> 00:13:37.468
FACS sorting, and so by the time four hours of FACS happens, metabolism

233
00:13:37.488 --> 00:13:40.788
has changed quite dramatically. So we thought we might

234
00:13:41.328 --> 00:13:42.468
take a different approach here.

235
00:13:44.268 --> 00:13:46.368
So our approach combines four things.

236
00:13:47.248 --> 00:13:48.668
First, the implantable microdevice.

237
00:13:48.908 --> 00:13:49.578
Next, we did

238
00:13:50.508 --> 00:13:53.088
CyTOF to tell us what cells are where.

239
00:13:53.548 --> 00:13:56.998
Then we do MALDI imaging mass

240
00:13:57.028 --> 00:14:00.848
spectrometry, which is my main contribution to this work, and

241
00:14:00.928 --> 00:14:04.668
then we also collaborated with Ernest Fraenkel and his talented graduate student,

242
00:14:04.708 --> 00:14:06.768
Veronica Pister, to

243
00:14:07.648 --> 00:14:11.068
increase our ability to do complicated computational

244
00:14:11.328 --> 00:14:13.308
analyses that integrate this

245
00:14:14.928 --> 00:14:17.088
incredible multimodal data.

246
00:14:20.708 --> 00:14:24.528
So we started off with this study, which was a continuation of a work that was

247
00:14:24.548 --> 00:14:26.068
done by Zuzana Tolarova.

248
00:14:27.388 --> 00:14:28.128
And Zuzana

249
00:14:29.208 --> 00:14:33.048
