00:29:36.470 --> 00:29:39.230
we get the first systemic measurements from imaging

509
00:29:40.830 --> 00:29:42.610
or from surgical specimens in some cases.

510
00:29:43.550 --> 00:29:47.450
And where this really comes to play is in treatment selection

511
00:29:47.470 --> 00:29:48.510
for patients. So

512
00:29:49.870 --> 00:29:50.030
the

513
00:29:52.350 --> 00:29:52.930
traditional

514
00:29:53.950 --> 00:29:55.870
selection

515
00:29:58.250 --> 00:30:02.050
of treatments is based on what's the standard of care for a given treatment,

516
00:30:02.870 --> 00:30:03.150
and then

517
00:30:05.030 --> 00:30:08.310
that is given to the patient, and we have to wait weeks to months until we know if

518
00:30:08.950 --> 00:30:11.870
that treatment actually works. And if it doesn't work, the patient goes on to the

519
00:30:11.930 --> 00:30:14.730
second-line treatment, and in some cases, the third line.

520
00:30:15.410 --> 00:30:19.030
There are many different cancer drugs to choose from and indications.

521
00:30:19.070 --> 00:30:20.470
They're often given in combination.

522
00:30:20.500 --> 00:30:24.062
So it's a very complex problem.And of course, the goal of precision

523
00:30:24.102 --> 00:30:27.682
medicine is to not have a patient go through those

524
00:30:27.742 --> 00:30:29.782
cycles of treatments that may not be effective,

525
00:30:31.142 --> 00:30:34.422
but instead to have the treatment identified that's going to be the most effective,

526
00:30:34.462 --> 00:30:35.702
and to give that right off the bat.

527
00:30:37.162 --> 00:30:38.942
There's a related problem in drug development.

528
00:30:39.842 --> 00:30:41.422
So, as everyone here knows,

529
00:30:43.862 --> 00:30:47.162
the path from developing a compound pre-clinically to having it

530
00:30:47.182 --> 00:30:51.102
approved is very long and costly, and I know those numbers

531
00:30:51.142 --> 00:30:53.942
are in flux, but I think they're only going in one direction, and that's up.

532
00:30:56.222 --> 00:30:57.142
And in addition to that,

533
00:30:58.042 --> 00:30:58.222
the

534
00:30:59.382 --> 00:31:03.342
majority of agents that make it to the late phases actually fail due to

535
00:31:03.352 --> 00:31:05.872
a lack of efficacy. And so understanding much earlier

536
00:31:07.162 --> 00:31:10.662
if a given drug is effective, and in what patient population or

537
00:31:10.682 --> 00:31:13.922
subpopulation it would be effective in, would be very valuable and would help us

538
00:31:13.962 --> 00:31:16.802
develop drugs faster and more effectively.

539
00:31:19.102 --> 00:31:19.922
So with that in mind,

540
00:31:20.782 --> 00:31:24.202
we wanted to develop an assay that would actually

541
00:31:24.282 --> 00:31:25.482
work in the patient,

542
00:31:26.482 --> 00:31:28.202
because we know that tumors

543
00:31:29.862 --> 00:31:33.642
do not just depend on the patient's genome, but

544
00:31:33.742 --> 00:31:37.272
also on the epigenome, the transcriptome, the proteome, metabolome, as Sean showed.

545
00:31:39.262 --> 00:31:42.302
And all those factors contribute to the phenotype, to the actual drug response.

546
00:31:43.622 --> 00:31:47.382
So several years ago, the FDA developed a concept

547
00:31:48.122 --> 00:31:51.862
called the Phase-zero Microdosing Concept as part of the Critical Path Initiative.

548
00:31:53.462 --> 00:31:56.462
And it provided for a streamlined

549
00:31:57.382 --> 00:32:01.042
regulatory process to test novel agents in patients,

550
00:32:04.522 --> 00:32:05.232
sort of faster

551
00:32:06.202 --> 00:32:09.542
and much more easily than for a traditional phase I systemic

552
00:32:09.642 --> 00:32:10.362
study.

553
00:32:11.302 --> 00:32:15.222
The original intent, or at least the original use cases, were

554
00:32:15.262 --> 00:32:15.582
more for

555
00:32:16.602 --> 00:32:19.842
PK studies. So a small amount of drug,

556
00:32:21.402 --> 00:32:24.042
and the threshold is usually 1% of the systemic dose,

557
00:32:25.962 --> 00:32:29.862
would be administered IV, and then we could learn how the drug distributes in the

558
00:32:29.882 --> 00:32:30.142
body.

559
00:32:32.082 --> 00:32:34.092
But the insight that we had, or the idea that we had,

560
00:32:36.062 --> 00:32:39.932
was that we could deliver that microdose directly into the tumor, and as

561
00:32:39.942 --> 00:32:41.312
long as it's less than 1%,

562
00:32:42.662 --> 00:32:46.102
and as long as we can keep it local inside the tumor, then we can actually have

563
00:32:46.162 --> 00:32:47.682
therapeutic level

564
00:32:48.962 --> 00:32:49.302
drug

565
00:32:51.142 --> 00:32:53.962
within the tumor, and we can measure how the tumor responds to those drugs.

566
00:32:54.011 --> 00:32:57.082
And that's how we came up with the implantable microdevice assay to actually make

567
00:32:57.102 --> 00:33:00.982
those measurements inside the patient, and to make those measurements not

568
00:33:01.042 --> 00:33:03.942
only for one drug, but for many drugs in parallel.

569
00:33:05.102 --> 00:33:06.222
So the way this assay works

570
00:33:08.582 --> 00:33:11.922
is that a small device that's about the size of a grain of

571
00:33:11.962 --> 00:33:14.462
rice and has a large number of reservoirs on it.

572
00:33:14.502 --> 00:33:17.282
It's typically about 20, although we have a few variations of that.

573
00:33:19.262 --> 00:33:22.662
And the device is delivered directly into the tumor with a biopsy needle, and then

574
00:33:22.722 --> 00:33:25.242
it resides in the tumor for a set period of time.

575
00:33:25.322 --> 00:33:28.102
Usually, it's about three to five days, but that can be varied based

576
00:33:29.262 --> 00:33:31.101
on the drugs and on the measurements we're trying to make.

577
00:33:33.202 --> 00:33:37.112
We always place multiple devices in the same tumor, so typically four

578
00:33:37.162 --> 00:33:37.622
to six,

579
00:33:39.882 --> 00:33:43.382
and that allows us to measure the response of the tumor to the same drug in

580
00:33:43.442 --> 00:33:45.822
different locations. So we understand the role of the local

581
00:33:45.882 --> 00:33:48.102
microenvironment

582
00:33:49.602 --> 00:33:51.062
in modulating drug responses.

583
00:33:52.402 --> 00:33:55.882
And what's really important is that we've now, and I'll show some data on that,

584
00:33:57.462 --> 00:33:59.722
delivered this into many different solid tumor types.

585
00:33:59.762 --> 00:34:02.742
So we think it's amenable in general

586
00:34:04.742 --> 00:34:06.962
to any solid tumor that can be reached with a biopsy,

587
00:34:08.243 --> 00:34:11.122
and we've done studies showing that there's no systemic

588
00:34:12.283 --> 00:34:15.303
drug exposure that's detectable, even with the most sensitive techniques.

589
00:34:15.342 --> 00:34:19.283
So we're able to deliver a drug. We can do

590
00:34:19.303 --> 00:34:23.243
it in a very controlled and precise way, and do it locally in a way that

591
00:34:23.303 --> 00:34:25.803
allows us to multiplex different measurements at the same time.

592
00:34:27.882 --> 00:34:31.763
So the way the workflow looks in the clinic is that the devices are

593
00:34:31.783 --> 00:34:35.703
placed in the tumor, and then when they come out, they're extracted with

594
00:34:35.803 --> 00:34:36.542
surrounding tissue,

595
00:34:37.422 --> 00:34:40.921
so that can either be harvested at the time of surgery or with the

596
00:34:41.882 --> 00:34:45.562
new version of the device that we have that can be retrieved with a second biopsy.

597
00:34:46.803 --> 00:34:48.442
And then this device tumor specimen

598
00:34:49.502 --> 00:34:53.382
is processed, either fresh frozen or FFPE, and then we section through

599
00:34:53.442 --> 00:34:55.422
that device tumor specimen,

600
00:34:56.962 --> 00:34:58.542
and we get a cross-section of the whole tumor

601
00:34:59.462 --> 00:35:02.882
with the device in the middle, and you have your different treatment zones that

602
00:35:02.942 --> 00:35:06.122
are in spatially confined regions, and you have

603
00:35:06.802 --> 00:35:10.702
untreated control tissue directly next to it that you can compare

604
00:35:10.762 --> 00:35:11.482
to your drug effect.

605
00:35:16.822 --> 00:35:19.022
What's also

606
00:35:19.842 --> 00:35:23.182
been the subject of a lot of work and development is being able to do this

607
00:35:23.222 --> 00:35:27.142
with many different modalities. So we've used a lot of small

608
00:35:27.182 --> 00:35:28.382
molecules and antibodies,

609
00:35:29.682 --> 00:35:31.262
and more recently, some ADCs,

610
00:35:32.502 --> 00:35:35.282
and even some cytokines. There's a somewhat different

611
00:35:36.722 --> 00:35:38.682
delivery and formulation mechanism for each, so

612
00:35:38.722 --> 00:35:42.622
we've had to optimize that. It's mostly based

613
00:35:42.642 --> 00:35:46.622
on polymers, and the polymers act as a sponge that can release each

614
00:35:46.662 --> 00:35:49.362
of the compounds in a controlled and precise manner.

615
00:35:49.402 --> 00:35:50.462
So we have

616
00:35:51.402 --> 00:35:51.522
the

617
00:35:52.442 --> 00:35:56.302
chance there to tune the exact concentration of drug

618
00:35:56.322 --> 00:35:58.442
that gets released into the tumor.

619
00:36:03.362 --> 00:36:07.302
And what's really important also is on the tissue that we take out and on which we

620
00:36:07.322 --> 00:36:09.142
do the measurements, we're able to see the drug

621
00:36:10.782 --> 00:36:14.002
distribution and the local drug concentration, and there's different ways to do

622
00:36:14.062 --> 00:36:16.322
that. And Sean showed a little bit

623
00:36:17.422 --> 00:36:19.302
on how mass spec is really useful for that.

624
00:36:19.402 --> 00:36:23.382
So what you can see here, for example, is a tumor cross-section

625
00:36:23.442 --> 00:36:27.222
where you have the device in the middle and you see your local delivery zone.

626
00:36:27.962 --> 00:36:30.322
You see a spatial gradient there. I'll talk more about that in a

627
00:36:30.362 --> 00:36:33.950
minute.But in addition to

628
00:36:33.990 --> 00:36:37.290
detecting the molecule directly, you can also detect some of

629
00:36:37.350 --> 00:36:41.310
the sort of formulation components or stabilizers that are part of the clinical

630
00:36:41.410 --> 00:36:43.870
formulation for almost all drugs.

631
00:36:44.970 --> 00:36:47.150
Or you can have fluorescent tags, for example,

632
00:36:48.449 --> 00:36:52.390
with which you can see the drug directly into the tissue, and these are examples

633
00:36:52.430 --> 00:36:55.730
here of different drugs. And there's also a few other techniques that we haven't

634
00:36:55.790 --> 00:36:55.950
used,

635
00:36:57.270 --> 00:37:00.870
but certainly you could use, for example, tissue capture microdissection into

636
00:37:00.970 --> 00:37:04.700
LC-MS or other techniques to quantitate the amount of drug and the gradient that

637
00:37:04.710 --> 00:37:05.069
you get.

638
00:37:08.070 --> 00:37:11.430
So, what's really important in order to understand how a drug works is to get the

639
00:37:11.470 --> 00:37:14.999
concentration right. So early on, we did a lot of

640
00:37:15.050 --> 00:37:18.070
studies trying to understand the

641
00:37:19.270 --> 00:37:22.690
local drug concentration that makes it to the tumor when you dose systemically.

642
00:37:23.570 --> 00:37:27.050
For some chemical agents, that's known from the

643
00:37:27.670 --> 00:37:31.030
literature, but for other agents, you have to do that measurement yourself.

644
00:37:31.080 --> 00:37:34.990
And so we figured out ways to tune the concentration of the drug locally, again,

645
00:37:35.030 --> 00:37:38.950
through that polymer formulation so that you can match locally

646
00:37:38.970 --> 00:37:41.250
what you would get in the tumor from systemic dosing.

647
00:37:43.150 --> 00:37:46.830
And then clinically here, an example from our GBM patients

648
00:37:46.870 --> 00:37:49.230
showing that you get a very

649
00:37:51.710 --> 00:37:53.250
consistent drug release profile

650
00:37:55.370 --> 00:37:57.770
based on these formulation techniques.

651
00:38:00.950 --> 00:38:02.390
So one interesting aspect of this is

652
00:38:03.310 --> 00:38:06.650
when we release drugs locally in the tumor from the reservoir, we get a

653
00:38:06.710 --> 00:38:09.630
concentration gradient that's distance dependent.

654
00:38:09.850 --> 00:38:12.890
So close to the reservoir you have higher concentrations, and then as you get

655
00:38:12.970 --> 00:38:14.770
further away, you have lower concentrations.

656
00:38:15.490 --> 00:38:19.450
And what that really allows you to do is sort of a localized PK/PD measurements

657
00:38:19.490 --> 00:38:22.250
for each of the different agents that are on the microdevice.

658
00:38:24.050 --> 00:38:27.630
And you can overlay the concentration gradient of the drug with

659
00:38:27.670 --> 00:38:28.190
measurements

660
00:38:29.390 --> 00:38:32.930
of drug effect or of efficacy, and there's a couple examples of that shown here.

661
00:38:32.990 --> 00:38:36.930
This one is for CLEAVE caspase-3, showing tumor apoptosis as

662
00:38:36.970 --> 00:38:40.750
a function of concentration, and on the right is an example of the

663
00:38:40.769 --> 00:38:44.470
androgen receptor for two different drugs from a

664
00:38:44.490 --> 00:38:45.530
prostate cancer patient.

665
00:38:46.930 --> 00:38:50.450
So, just two different examples of different PD

666
00:38:50.520 --> 00:38:52.670
readouts that you can make spatially

667
00:38:54.890 --> 00:38:56.990
by taking advantage of that drug release gradient.

668
00:38:59.710 --> 00:39:02.730
And then, as Sean mentioned, we have a lot of efforts underway to

669
00:39:02.790 --> 00:39:05.070
integrate different types of measurements.

670
00:39:06.050 --> 00:39:09.170
So this is an example here of spatial transcriptomic

671
00:39:10.970 --> 00:39:14.890
profiling of cells, and you can use that information to understand

672
00:39:14.910 --> 00:39:17.240
the effect of the drug on

673
00:39:18.350 --> 00:39:21.350
the different cell types that are present in the tumor treatment zone.

674
00:39:22.350 --> 00:39:26.170
So not just the bulk measurement, but even at the single-cell level and certainly

675
00:39:26.190 --> 00:39:28.490
at the cell type level to understand

676
00:39:29.350 --> 00:39:29.530
the

677
00:39:31.270 --> 00:39:34.330
specific effects, for example, on the tumor cells versus the T cells,

678
00:39:35.770 --> 00:39:36.250
and so on.

679
00:39:38.510 --> 00:39:40.290
So one of the early studies that we did,

680
00:39:41.410 --> 00:39:43.530
and this is still a preclinical study,

681
00:39:44.350 --> 00:39:47.290
a few years ago, was to see, okay, can we use these measurements to actually

682
00:39:47.410 --> 00:39:51.390
predict systemic sensitivity of the tumor and ultimately of

683
00:39:51.410 --> 00:39:51.950
the patient

684
00:39:53.170 --> 00:39:54.650
to different drugs?

685
00:39:57.050 --> 00:40:00.190
And in this study, what we did is we had a number of different agents that were

686
00:40:01.690 --> 00:40:03.830
delivered into different tumor models.

687
00:40:03.850 --> 00:40:07.610
And for each of the agents, we noticed that there was a very unique tumor

688
00:40:07.690 --> 00:40:08.810
drug response signature,

689
00:40:09.710 --> 00:40:13.290
and that consisted of an effect on the tumor cells, but it also

690
00:40:13.390 --> 00:40:16.450
consisted of effects on the macrophages and on the T cells.

691
00:40:17.010 --> 00:40:20.430
And we found and then showed in systemic studies

692
00:40:21.470 --> 00:40:25.090
that the local phenotype that you get from

693
00:40:25.170 --> 00:40:28.910
the drug exposure can be used to

694
00:40:28.930 --> 00:40:32.130
predict a combination agent that's going to lead to a superior efficacy.

695
00:40:32.990 --> 00:40:36.510
So in the example of palbociclib, we see the emergence of

696
00:40:36.550 --> 00:40:40.390
protumorigenic macrophages in the treatment zone, and those can be combined then

697
00:40:41.690 --> 00:40:45.390
very effectively with an anti-CD4 antibody,

698
00:40:45.930 --> 00:40:49.610
and you see that that gives you the superior response. Same with the venetoclax.

699
00:40:52.530 --> 00:40:55.960
Whereas the panobinostat, for example, you see the antigen-presenting neutrophils,

700
00:40:56.490 --> 00:40:58.550
and those are effectively treated with

701
00:40:59.470 --> 00:41:03.370
an anti-CSFR antibody. So we showed that we can make

702
00:41:03.380 --> 00:41:06.010
this measurement for different drugs in the tumor, and for each of them,

703
00:41:07.270 --> 00:41:11.250
based on the actual responses, we can combine that treatment

704
00:41:11.310 --> 00:41:13.730
with an immunotherapy and get a superior response.

705
00:41:14.410 --> 00:41:17.070
So then the next step, of course, was, okay, we want to do this in the patient.

706
00:41:18.990 --> 00:41:20.450
And so we,

707
00:41:22.750 --> 00:41:25.910
since then, have initiated 13

708
00:41:26.850 --> 00:41:30.600
clinical trials in different tumor types, have placed over 350 devices into

709
00:41:30.630 --> 00:41:31.040
patients

710
00:41:32.030 --> 00:41:35.329
with an excellent safety profile. There hasn't been a single serious adverse event.

711
00:41:36.930 --> 00:41:38.650
And we've tested a lot of different therapies,

712
00:41:39.510 --> 00:41:42.750
both on the small molecule side and the large molecule side, and a lot of

713
00:41:42.810 --> 00:41:43.790
combinations as well.

714
00:41:47.090 --> 00:41:50.730
And another aspect that's exciting that I'll say a little bit more about at the end

715
00:41:50.790 --> 00:41:54.390
is the ability to use this platform to test novel

716
00:41:54.490 --> 00:41:57.650
compounds that are not yet approved,

717
00:41:58.610 --> 00:42:02.090
and, most recently, even pre-IND agents with a

718
00:42:02.930 --> 00:42:04.350
very minimal tox package,

719
00:42:05.810 --> 00:42:09.190
and to be able to generate clinical data much earlier and faster than you normally

720
00:42:09.230 --> 00:42:11.590
would with a traditional Phase 1 approach.

721
00:42:12.710 --> 00:42:16.570
So I'd like to show a few applications of what we think are the three

722
00:42:16.690 --> 00:42:19.690
primary use cases for this intra-tumor platform.

723
00:42:19.750 --> 00:42:20.230
The first one

724
00:42:21.070 --> 00:42:24.390
is maybe the most obvious one, that's the personalized selection of treatment.

725
00:42:25.370 --> 00:42:27.470
So the idea would be you put this device in a patient,

726
00:42:28.350 --> 00:42:31.810
you load it with a lot of different approved agents that are relevant for that

727
00:42:31.830 --> 00:42:35.750
specific cancer type, then you measure how the patient's tumor responds

728
00:42:35.810 --> 00:42:39.310
to all the different treatments, and you pick the one that is

729
00:42:39.850 --> 00:42:43.020
the most effective.The second

730
00:42:43.030 --> 00:42:46.710
application is on the drug development side, so to be able to get

731
00:42:46.760 --> 00:42:49.780
human data much earlier, much faster, and to understand

732
00:42:50.980 --> 00:42:52.600
target engagement mechanism,

733
00:42:53.860 --> 00:42:55.140
dose-dependent efficacy,

734
00:42:57.140 --> 00:43:00.520
and biomarkers. And then the last application I'll say a little bit about at the

735
00:43:00.560 --> 00:43:00.700
end,

736
00:43:01.800 --> 00:43:04.140
and that's to use the fact that you have

737
00:43:05.920 --> 00:43:09.300
a large number of pharmacological perturbations that you're putting on a single

738
00:43:09.400 --> 00:43:09.700
tumor,

739
00:43:10.720 --> 00:43:10.990
and to

740
00:43:12.100 --> 00:43:16.060
essentially ask, what can I learn from the many perturbations that I can't

741
00:43:16.100 --> 00:43:16.780
learn from one?

742
00:43:18.260 --> 00:43:18.820
And we've now,

743
00:43:20.760 --> 00:43:24.540
through these studies, built a sample library of over 6,000 unique

744
00:43:24.580 --> 00:43:27.960
tumor drug phenotypes, meaning tumor sections that are treated with a unique drug

745
00:43:28.700 --> 00:43:29.900
in a unique patient.

746
00:43:31.960 --> 00:43:35.200
And we're working on some modeling and machine learning-assisted

747
00:43:35.260 --> 00:43:38.980
ways to understand that data and to integrate the biomarkers

748
00:43:39.800 --> 00:43:41.680
into specific,

749
00:43:42.840 --> 00:43:46.000
potentially better treatment outcomes and treatment hypotheses.

750
00:43:47.580 --> 00:43:51.420
So I'd like to walk you through an example of how that process is played

751
00:43:51.480 --> 00:43:52.160
out in real-time.

752
00:43:53.760 --> 00:43:57.360
And so this is sort of the story of our clinical study in

753
00:43:57.380 --> 00:44:01.160
glioblastoma. So as everyone here knows, it's an

754
00:44:01.740 --> 00:44:03.960
extremely deadly disease, one of the most deadly tumors,

755
00:44:06.060 --> 00:44:06.800
and there are

756
00:44:07.980 --> 00:44:10.040
relatively short times to progression and

757
00:44:10.880 --> 00:44:14.760
terrible clinical outcomes. So the purpose of this study is to

